An IndexOutOfBoundsException is triggered when a program attempts to access an an element at an index that is greater than or equal to the size of the an array (or any indexed set of elements). The problem in your code lies in the if statement inside of the for loop:

    if( (items.get(i).getName().equals(items.get( i + 1).getName()) &amp;&amp; check year)
Imagine that you have reached the last element in your traversal of the LinkedList. The above statement seeks to compare this last element with the element at the next index. Clearly, this is nonsensical; there is no next element. 

The straightforward way to eliminate duplicates within some indexed list L is to have a simple nested loop:

    for(int i = 0; i &lt; L.length; i++){
         curr_item = L[i]
         for(int j = i + 1; j &lt; L.length; j++){
               if(L[j] == L[i])
                   L[j] = null; //or some other remedy

&gt; I try with this and because there&#39;s no item after three and get
&gt; arrayoutofbound exception.

It must be [IndexOutOfBoundsException][1], not `arrayoutofbound`. The `IndexOutOfBoundsException` occurs when the index is out of range (`index &lt; 0 || index &gt;= size()`). In your case, you need to terminate the loop before `items.size() -1` as you are trying to access `items.get( i + 1)`. It should be

    for(int i = 0; i &lt; items.size() - 1; i++)

Another problem with your approach is that you are comparing only with the immediate next element whereas the matching element can be anywhere in the list. Therefore, you need to compare the elements using nested loops i.e. an element needs to be compared with all remaining elements until a match is found and as soon as the match is found, remove the matching element and stop the process.

